\begin_layout Example
(Gamma distribution with known scale parameter) The density of the gamma distribution with known scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>0$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\PP\big(R_{t}=r\mid X_{t},\Fcal_{t}\big)=e^{-\frac{r}{\theta}}\exp\big(z_{t}\log r-\log\Gamma(1+z_{t})-(1+z_{t})\log\theta\big).
\]

\end_inset

Here we set 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)=e^{-\frac{r}{\theta}}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $h(r)=\log r$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m(z_{t})=\log\Gamma(1+z_{t})+(1+z_{t})\log\theta$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $\EE[r_{t}|X_{t},\Fcal_{t}]=\frac{\alpha}{\theta}=\frac{\EE[\log r_{t}]}{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 (How about making a Table of univariate distributions that indicates natural and non-natural distributions?).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is which provides the intrinsic weighting of the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $m(z)$
\end_inset

 is a twice continuously differentiable function used for normalizing the distribution.
 Besides,
 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\RR\to\RR$
\end_inset

 is the dispersion function controlling the variability of the distribution,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\RR$
\end_inset

 is a known parameter.
 The expectation and variance of the exponential family distribution can be calculated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\EE[r\mid z]=\mu(z)\triangleq m'(z)\quad\text{and}\quad\Var(r\mid z)=g(\tau)m''(z)$
\end_inset


