\begin_layout Paragraph
GLM-UCB Method and Potentially Large Constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The canonical algorithm for the GLB problem is GLM-UCB
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Filippi2010}
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 which resolves the exploration–exploitation trade-off with an upper-confidence-bound strategy
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Agrawal1995}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Under Assumptions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

1 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2 and an additional condition that the reward 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 is non-negative and almost surely bounded for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[T]$
\end_inset

,
 GLM-UCB achieves the regret of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ocal\bigl(\kappa(\log T)^{3/2}\sqrt{T}\bigr),$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Ocal(\cdot)$
\end_inset

-notation is used to highlight the dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 and the time horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 The dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 matches that of the linear case,
 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\Ocal}(\sqrt{T})$
\end_inset

 rate is nearly optimal
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Dani2008}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The bottleneck lies in its 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 dependence on the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

,
 which is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa\triangleq\frac{1}{c_{\mu}}=\frac{1}{\inf_{\xb\in\Xcal_{[T]},\,\theta\in\Theta}\mu'(\xb^{\top}\theta)}\quad\text{and}\quad\kappa_{*}\triangleq\frac{1}{\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T}\mu'(\xb_{t,*}^{\top}\theta_{*})},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\bigl\{\theta\in\RR^{d}\mid\norm{\theta}_{2}\le S\bigr\},\qquad\Xcal_{[T]}=\bigcup_{t\in[T]}\Xcal_{t}.$
\end_inset

 In the above,
 we also define 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{*}$
\end_inset

 to reflect the local curvature at the optimal actions.
 The linear dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 in GLM-UCB is generally undesirable,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 can be prohibitively large in practice.
 Notable examples include the Bernoulli distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(z)=1/(1+e^{-z})$
\end_inset

 and the Poisson distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(z)=e^{z}$
\end_inset

,
 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=\Ocal(e^{S})$
\end_inset

,
 growing exponentially with the parameter-norm bound 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
2.2
\begin_inset space \quad{}
\end_inset

New Progress with Self-Concordance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The undesirable linear dependence on
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 has motivated the development of algorithms with improved theoretical guarantees.
 By leveraging the 
\emph on
self-concordance
\emph default
 of the loss,
 rooted in convex optimization and later used in the analysis of logistic regression
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Bach2010}
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 recent studies
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Russac2021,Lee2024,Sawarni2024}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 have derived regret bounds with substantially reduced dependence on
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 for GLB.
 Following this line,
 we also adopt the self-concordance assumption here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

[
\end_layout

\end_inset

Self-Concordance
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The link function satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mu''(z)|\le R\cdot\mu'(z)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\RR$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{assumption}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assumption
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3 holds for many widely used GLMs.
 For GLMs where the reward is almost surely bounded in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $[0,R]$
\end_inset

,
 the link function satisfies Assumption
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3 with coefficient
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Sawarni2024}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For example,
 the Bernoulli distribution is 1-self-concordant.
 Many unbounded GLMs also satisfy self-concordance,
 including the Gaussian distribution (
\begin_inset Formula $R=0$
\end_inset

),
 Poisson distribution (
\begin_inset Formula $R=1$
\end_inset

),
 and Exponential distribution (
\begin_inset Formula $R=0$
\end_inset

).
 Leveraging self-concordance,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citet{Lee2024}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citet{Sawarni2024}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 established improved regret bounds of order
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Ocal(T/\kappa_{*})$
\end_inset

.
 In these results,
 the potentially large constant
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{*}$
\end_inset

 appears in the denominator,
 which largely improves the
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Ocal(\kappa\sqrt{T})$
\end_inset

 bound by
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citet{Filippi2010}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 However,
 their methods still incur
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Ocal(t)$
\end_inset

 time and space complexities per round.
 Our goal is to design a method with low computational cost while maintaining strong regret guarantees.
\end_layout

